<section xml:id="lesson5_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation: Vectors</title>

  <section xml:id="vector_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vector Quantum Representation</title>

    <p>
      The purpose of vector notation is to allow us to calculate the output of quantum
      gates.
      Vector notation loses some of the explicit information in bra-ket notation -
      namely, the
      information about what each probability amplitude is tied to. Instead, we have
      to remember
      the proper order.
</p>

    <p> Bra-ket notation is always sorted by the value in the ket - the sorting order is,
      from left to right, smallest to largest. Vector notation uses the same order - smallest to
      largest - but it is depicted from to bottom.</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.brakettovector.png" width="30%" />
    </p>

    <p> Here are some examples: </p>


    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.brakettovectorexamples.png" width="30%" />
    </p>

    <p> You have to be careful, though, to express bra-ket notation in the proper order.
      If the bra-ket order is incorrect, then you might accidentally put the terms in the
      wrong
      locations in the vector. </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.wrongorder.png" width="30%" />
    </p>

    <p> Put 2 question checks here - bra-ket to vector and then back again </p>

  </section>


  <section xml:id="vector_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vector State Simplification</title>

    <p> Generally, the state simplification rules are the same for vectors and for
      bra-ket notation,
      with one major exception - you can never remove a state! You must retain the 0. </p>

    <p> 1. The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order
      (starting with all 0's and ending with all 1's). This is even more important for
      vector
      notation because we don't explicitly write the outcome. </p>

    <p> 2. You may NOT omit any term whose probability is 0. (make this text bright
      red!!)
      (make images of these two, both bra-ket and vector: |0> and pair it with the
      state: 50/50 00 vs 11)
</p>

    <p> 3. If all outcomes are the same probability, people rarely omit the leading term.
      They do, however, factor out a common fractional component and put that in front of the
      vector.
      (make "rarely omit" red text, plus the last sentence)
</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.pullfactor.png" width="30%" />
    </p>

    <p> 4. The state with all 0's is never in negative phase </p>

    <p> Question check - the state |1>, then the state 50/50 |01>, |10> </p>


  </section>


</section>
